"title": "6166: flesh, sinful nature",
"media_type": "Text",
"index_reference": "6166: flesh, sinful nature",
"language": "eng",
"review_level": "None",
"content": "<p>The physical aspect of human beings, which distinguishes them from God and is therefore frequently used in the NT as a symbol of human sinful nature in contrast with God's perfection. (The Greek word for “flesh” is sometimes translated by other words and phrases in the passages cited in this theme.).</p>\n<h2>Flesh as the bodily substance of human beings</h2>\n<h3>As individuals or in relation to others</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps84:2\">PSA 84:2</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen2:23-Gen2:24\">GEN 2:23–2:24</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen29:14\">GEN 29:14</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Cor15:39\">1CO 15:39</a>GAL <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Cor2:20\">2:20</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Phil1:22-Phil1:24\">PHP 1:22–1:24</a></p>\n<h3>As the means by which Jesus Christ identified with the human race to bring salvation</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/John1:14\">JHN 1:14</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Eph2:15\">EPH 2:15</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Heb10:20\">HEB 10:20</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1John4:2\">1JN 4:2</a></p>\n<h3>As subject to mortality</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa40:6-Isa40:7\">ISA 40:6–40:7</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps78:39\">PSA 78:39</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts2:31\">ACT 2:31</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Cor15:50\">1CO 15:50</a></p>\n<h3>As subject to weakness</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Chr32:8\">2CH 32:8</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps73:26\">PSA 73:26</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt26:41\">MAT 26:41</a> parallel <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark14:38\">MRK 14:38</a></p>\n<h2>Flesh as contrasting human nature with God's perfection</h2>\n<h3>The powerlessness of human beings contrasted with God's eternal power</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa31:3\">ISA 31:3</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/John3:6\">JHN 3:6</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/John6:63\">JHN 6:63</a></p>\n<h3>Human or worldly standards contrasted with God's standards</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/John8:15\">JHN 8:15</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Cor1:26\">1CO 1:26</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Cor5:16\">2CO 5:16</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Cor10:3-2Cor10:4\">2CO 10:3–10:4</a></p>\n<h2>Flesh as denoting the sinful nature of human beings</h2>\n<h3>The tendency to sin</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rom7:18\">ROM 7:18</a></strong> <em>Paul does not mean that no goodness at all exists in people; nor that the physical aspect of human beings is inherently evil. He means that humans are invariably infected by evil and subject to its power.</em> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer17:5\">JER 17:5</a></p>\n<h3>The conflict in human experience between the sinful nature and the Spirit of God</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gal5:17\">GAL 5:17</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rom8:4-Rom8:9\">ROM 8:4–8:9</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gal5:19-Gal5:25\">GAL 5:19–5:25</a></p>\n<h2>The sinful nature is opposed to God and his will</h2>\n<h3>This opposition finds expression in a range of acts and attitudes</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gal5:19-Gal5:21\">GAL 5:19–5:21</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rom7:14-Rom7:25\">ROM 7:14–7:25</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rom8:7\">ROM 8:7</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rom13:13-Rom13:14\">ROM 13:13–13:14</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Cor6:9-1Cor6:11\">1CO 6:9–6:11</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Eph5:5\">EPH 5:5</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jas1:14-Jas1:15\">JAS 1:14–1:15</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Pet2:11\">1PE 2:11</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Pet2:10\">2PE 2:10</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Pet2:18\">2PE 2:18</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1John2:16\">1JN 2:16</a></p>\n<h3>Confidence in the law is futile</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rom8:3\">ROM 8:3</a></strong> <em>Because of the sinfulness of human nature, God's law is powerless to bring people into relationship with God</em>; <strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gal3:3\">GAL 3:3</a></strong> <em>Even the attempt to find acceptance with God through keeping his law is an act of the sinful nature because it involves rejecting his offer of salvation through his grace.</em> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rom7:25\">ROM 7:25</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Phil3:3-Phil3:9\">PHP 3:3–3:9</a></p>\n<h3>The sinful nature controls human behaviour in ways which run counter to God's purpose</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rom8:8\">ROM 8:8</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rom7:5\">ROM 7:5</a></p>\n<h2>The sinful nature therefore makes people subject to God's judgment and to death</h2>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rom8:13\">ROM 8:13</a></strong>; <strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Eph2:3\">EPH 2:3</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gal6:8\">GAL 6:8</a></p>\n<h2>Believers are not controlled by the sinful nature</h2>\n<h3>Through Jesus Christ's entering into human flesh, God delivers from the power and consequences of human sinfulness</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rom8:3\">ROM 8:3</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Eph2:15\">EPH 2:15</a></p>\n<h3>Believers have crucified the sinful nature</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rom7:5-Rom7:6\">ROM 7:5–7:6</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rom8:8-Rom8:9\">ROM 8:8–8:9</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gal5:24\">GAL 5:24</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Col2:11\">COL 2:11</a></p>\n<h3>The power of God's Spirit enables believers to continue to resist the sinful nature</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rom8:13\">ROM 8:13</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rom13:14\">ROM 13:14</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gal5:13\">GAL 5:13</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Col3:5-Col3:6\">COL 3:5–3:6</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Pet2:11\">1PE 2:11</a></p>\n<h3>God's provision of church discipline in eliminating the sinful nature</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Cor5:5\">1CO 5:5</a></strong> <em>The discipline of excluding a sinner from the church community is intended to bring him to repentance and so abandon his sinful course of action. Repentance provoked by physical suffering is possibly also in mind.</em></p>",
